{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.02,0.04,0.78,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114173"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6447"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96173"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"408"},{"type":"tags","id":"2390"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114173"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of progressive thickening and discolouration of her right lower leg. She reports no associated pain or itching. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, hypothyroidism, and right nephrectomy for renal cell carcinoma two years ago. Her most recent cancer surveillance three months ago showed no evidence of recurrence. Her medications include perindopril, metformin and thyroxine, though she reports variable compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 136/84 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her BMI is 34 kg/m2. The changes in the right lower leg are shown (Image). The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peripheral arterial disease","Cellulitis","Lymphatic obstruction","Chronic venous insufficiency","Myxoedema"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of lipodermatosclerosis, a chronic inflammatory condition characterised by skin induration and hyperpigmentation of the lower legs. In severe case the leg may have an \u0027inverted champagne bottle\u0027 appearance. The condition typically affects overweight women over 40 years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic venous insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is the underlying cause of lipodermatosclerosis. The condition results from sustained venous hypertension leading to inflammation, fibrosis, and characteristic skin changes. Risk factors present in this patient include female sex, obesity, and middle age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral arterial disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with intermittent claudication, cool extremities, and diminished pulses. The skin changes would be more likely to include hair loss, shiny skin, and ulceration rather than the induration and hyperpigmentation seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute bacterial infection of the skin and soft tissues, presenting with erythema, warmth, tenderness, and often systemic symptoms. The chronic nature and lack of acute inflammatory signs make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause both pitting and non-pitting oedema. It tends to cause pitting oedema in the early stages of the condition, which can progress to non-pitting oedema in later stages due to fibrosis and tissue thickening. Pitting oedema is worse at the end of the day and improves with elevation. While this patient has had previous surgery, the unilateral right nephrectomy would not typically cause lower limb lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyxoedema\u003C/strong\u003E from hypothyroidism causes bilateral, non-pitting oedema with dry, cool skin. While this patient has hypothyroidism, the unilateral presentation and specific skin changes are not consistent with myxoedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lipodermatosclerosis is characterised by indurated, hyperpigmented skin changes in the lower leg and is a manifestation of chronic venous insufficiency.","Risk factors for lipodermatosclerosis include obesity, female sex, and age over 40 years.","The condition typically presents with painless skin changes that progress gradually over months."],"references":["Millan SB, Gan R, Townsend PE. Venous Ulcers: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2019; 100:298-305."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96173"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20777"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20777"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rqaLblQinoCBhDjeVxmvHHBtMXSOZz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rqaLblQinoCBhDjeVxmvHHBtMXSOZz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type"